context:
The Pre-Health Sciences Pathway to Advanced Diplomas and Degrees (A108) program at George Brown College is designed for students who have a previous degree in any field and aim to apply to Doctor of Medicine (MD) programs, specifically St. George’s University in Grenada, West Indies. This one-year Ontario College Certificate program helps students meet the science requirements for MD applications by providing them with the necessary prerequisite courses. The program is delivered in a hybrid format and consists of two semesters.

Leadership Claim:
Graduates from this program have the opportunity to apply to St. George’s University, Grenada, West Indies, for their Doctor of Medicine (MD) program with the science requirements met through completing courses in the A108 program at George Brown College.

Program Overview:
The Pre-Health Sciences Pathway to Advanced Diplomas and Degrees (A108) program prepares students to apply for and be successful in health sciences programs at the advanced diploma or degree level. Students will explore potential career opportunities in various health science fields and identify educational pathways tailored to their career goals.

Students should note that if they are seeking a program to prepare them with the admission requirements for one-year certificate or two-year diploma health sciences programs, they must apply to George Brown’s Pre-Health Sciences Pathway to Certificates and Diplomas (A109) program.

Program Structure:
The A108 program consists of two semesters delivered in a hybrid format, with both online and on-campus components. The program covers various science subjects essential for medical applications and prepares students to meet the academic requirements for MD programs.

Courses:
Students will take the following courses:

Semester 1:

* BIOL 123 - Human Anatomy and Physiology I
* CHEM 131 - General Chemistry I
* MATH 065 - University Mathematics for Science and Engineering Students
* PHYS 131 - Physics for Life Sciences I

Semester 2:

* BIOL 124 - Human Anatomy and Physiology II
* CHEM 132 - General Chemistry II
* MATH 065 - University Mathematics for Science and Engineering Students (repeat)
* PHYS 132 - Physics for Life Sciences II

Tuition & Fees:
Domestic Students: $3,876.00
International Students: $17,504.00

Admission Requirements:
Applicants must have a completed bachelor’s degree or higher from a recognized post-secondary institution in any field. In addition, they should meet the following requirements:

* English language proficiency (ELT) for international students
* Minimum overall average of 60% in their most recent academic record

Program Outcomes:
Upon successful completion of this program, graduates will be prepared to apply to health sciences programs at the advanced diploma or degree level. They will have gained a solid foundation in essential science subjects and will possess the necessary skills and knowledge to pursue careers in various health science fields.

Contact Us:
For more information about the Pre-Health Sciences Pathway to Advanced Diplomas and Degrees (A108) program, please contact the George Brown College Admissions office at 416-415-2000 or admiss@georgebrown.ca. You can also visit the college's website at www.georgebrown.ca for more details on application deadlines and requirements.

* Tuition fees are subject to change based on Ontario government funding decisions.
** International student tuition includes a non-refundable application fee of $150 CAD.

The Pre-Health Sciences Pathway to Advanced Diplomas and Degrees (A108) program prepares students to apply for and be successful in health sciences programs at the advanced diploma or degree level. Students will explore potential career opportunities in various health science fields and identify educational pathways tailored to their career goals.

Students should note that if they are seeking a program to prepare them with the admission requirements for one-year certificate or two-year diploma health sciences programs, they must apply to George Brown’s Pre-Health Sciences Pathway to Certificates and Diplomas (A109) program.

Program Structure:
The A108 program consists of two semesters delivered in a hybrid format, with both online and on-campus components. The program covers various science subjects essential for medical applications and prepares students to meet the academic requirements for MD programs.

Courses:
Students will take the following courses:

Semester 1:

* BIOL 123 - Human Anatomy and Physiology I
* CHEM 131 - General Chemistry I
* MATH 065 - University Mathematics for Science and Engineering Students
* PHYS 131 - Physics for Life Sciences I

Semester 2:

* BIOL 124 - Human Anatomy and Physiology II
* CHEM 132 - General Chemistry II
* MATH 065 - University Mathematics for Science and Engineering Students (repeat)
* PHYS 132 - Physics for Life Sciences II

Tuition & Fees:
Domestic Students: $3,876.00
International Students: $17,504.00

Admission Requirements:
Applicants must have a completed bachelor’s degree or higher from a recognized post-secondary institution in any field. In addition, they should meet the following requirements:

* English language proficiency (ELT) for international students
* Minimum overall average of 60% in their most recent academic record

Program Outcomes:
Upon successful completion of this program, graduates will be prepared to apply to health sciences programs at the advanced diploma or degree level. They will have gained a solid foundation in essential science subjects and will possess the necessary skills and knowledge to pursue careers in various health science fields.

Contact Us:
For more information about the Pre-Health Sciences Pathway to Advanced Diplomas and Degrees (A108) program, please contact the George Brown College Admissions office at 416-415-2000 or admiss@georgebrown.ca. You can also visit the college's website at www.georgebrown.ca for more details on application deadlines and requirements.

* Tuition fees are subject to change based on Ontario government funding decisions.
** International student tuition includes a non-refundable application fee of $150 CAD.

George Brown College's Pre-Health Sciences Pathway to Advanced Diplomas and Degrees (A108) program is designed to prepare students for entry into advanced diploma or degree-level health sciences programs. This full-time program strengthens existing knowledge and builds new skills in areas such as communication, mathematics, human anatomy, biology, physics, organic/inorganic chemistry, and English.

Students who complete this program can apply to various advanced diploma programs at George Brown College including Dental Hygiene (S134), Dental Technology (S100), Denturism (S101), and Hearing Instrument Specialist (S117). Additionally, graduates are eligible to apply to external degree programs, such as the Bachelor of Health Sciences at Queen's University (BHSc) and Trent University for various Bachelor of Sciences degrees (not including Bachelor of Science - Nursing). Furthermore, students can also apply for the Bachelor of Science in Nursing (BScN) program.

If a student is interested in a program that will prepare them with the admission requirements to apply to a one-year certificate or two-year diploma health sciences program, they should apply to George Brown’s Pre-Health Sciences Pathway to Certificates and Diplomas (A109).

Program Title: Health Sciences - Biological and Chemical Foundations

Program Information:
This is a two-semester education elective program offered by George Brown College in Toronto, Canada. The program aims to provide students with foundational knowledge of biological and chemical concepts related to health sciences. It covers topics such as genetics and epigenetics, structure and function of the human body, chemistry, physics laws and concepts, and mathematics applications. Students will also develop a personal strategy for academic, career, and professional development in the health sciences or other science-related fields.

Admission Requirements:
1. Ontario Secondary School Diploma or equivalent

Additional Information:
- Tuition fees: $3,876 (Domestic) / $17,504 (International) for the first two semesters (subject to change)
- Financial assistance is available through OSAP, but eligibility has yet to be reviewed by the Ministry
- International students should refer to the International Fees and Related Costs page for more information

Program Learning Outcomes:
Upon completion of the program, students will be able to:
1. Examine biological concepts, processes, and systems of the human body, including genetics and epigenetics, as well as the structure, function, and properties of molecules, cells, tissues, and organ systems in relation to homeostasis, physical development, and health.
2. Examine concepts, processes, and systems of chemistry, including atomic and molecular structure, quantities in chemical reactions, solutions and solubility, acids and bases, organic chemistry, and biochemistry, in relation to health and the human body.
3. Solve numeric problems and interpret data related to health sciences and other science-related fields using mathematical concepts, including algebra, probability, and statistics.
4. Use health sciences and other science-related language and terminology appropriately to communicate clearly, concisely, and correctly in written, spoken, and visual forms.
5. Prepare a personal strategy and plan for academic, career, and professional development in the health sciences or other science-related fields.
6. Investigate health sciences and science-related questions, problems, and evidence using the scientific method.
7. Examine fundamental physics laws and concepts and their application to health sciences and other science-related fields.

Upon completion of the program, students will be able to:

2. Examine concepts, processes, and systems of chemistry, including atomic and molecular structure, quantities in chemical reactions, solutions and solubility, acids and bases, organic chemistry, and biochemistry, in relation to health and the human body.
3. Solve numeric problems and interpret data related to health sciences and other science-related fields using mathematical concepts, including algebra, probability, and statistics.
4. Use health sciences and other science-related language and terminology appropriately to communicate clearly, concisely, and correctly in written, spoken, and visual forms.
5. Prepare a personal strategy and plan for academic, career, and professional development in the health sciences or other science-related fields.
6. Investigate health sciences and science-related questions, problems, and evidence using the scientific method.
7. Examine fundamental physics laws and concepts and their application to health sciences and other science-related fields.
